<h2><span class="mw-headline" id="History">History</span><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="/w/index.php?title=Pegasystems&amp;action=edit&amp;section=1" title="Edit section: History">edit</a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></h2>
<h3><span class="mw-headline" id="Early_history">Early history</span><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="/w/index.php?title=Pegasystems&amp;action=edit&amp;section=2" title="Edit section: Early history">edit</a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></h3>
<p><a href="/wiki/Alan_Trefler" title="Alan Trefler">Alan Trefler</a> founded Pegasystems in 1983 at the age of 27, in <a href="/wiki/Cambridge,_Massachusetts" title="Cambridge, Massachusetts">Cambridge, Massachusetts</a>.<sup id="cite_ref-Bglobe-trefler_7-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Bglobe-trefler-7">&#91;7&#93;</a></sup> Prior to founding the company, in the early 1980s Trefler had developed <a href="/wiki/Computer" title="Computer">computer</a> systems that could play <a href="/wiki/Chess" title="Chess">chess</a>.<sup id="cite_ref-forbes_1-2" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-forbes-1">&#91;1&#93;</a></sup> During the company's early years it focused on providing case management, namely for companies such as <a href="/wiki/American_Express" title="American Express">American Express</a>.<sup id="cite_ref-forbes_1-3" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-forbes-1">&#91;1&#93;</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-mashable_11-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-mashable-11">&#91;11&#93;</a></sup> Trefler recollects that when he started Pegasystems, he wanted to create software that eased the heavy lifting that business people deal with, as well as software that understood how business-people wanted things to work, commenting "it turns out to be a fairly hard problem to solve."<sup id="cite_ref-forbes_1-4" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-forbes-1">&#91;1&#93;</a></sup> An article in <i><a href="/wiki/Computerworld" title="Computerworld">Computerworld</a></i> traces <a href="/wiki/Business_rules_engine" title="Business rules engine">business rules engine</a> to the early 1990s and to products from the likes of Pegasystems, <a href="/wiki/Fair_Isaac" class="mw-redirect" title="Fair Isaac">Fair Isaac</a> Corp and <a href="/wiki/ILOG" title="ILOG">ILOG</a>.<sup id="cite_ref-12" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-12">&#91;12&#93;</a></sup> As a private company, Pegasystems was "bootstrapped" initially, but did not take on outside investors.<sup id="cite_ref-forbes_1-5" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-forbes-1">&#91;1&#93;</a></sup> The company <a href="/wiki/Public_company" title="Public company">went public</a> in 1996 with initial and secondary public offerings,<sup id="cite_ref-sec-probe_13-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-sec-probe-13">&#91;13&#93;</a></sup>  and began trading on <a href="/wiki/NASDAQ" class="mw-redirect" title="NASDAQ">NASDAQ</a> under the symbol PEGA. Raising several millions in funding in the process, going public freed the company from needing to pursue <a href="/wiki/Venture_capital" title="Venture capital">venture capital</a> investments.<sup id="cite_ref-forbes_1-6" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-forbes-1">&#91;1&#93;</a></sup> Pegasystems entered a period of financial trouble in the late 1990s, following a dispute with its accountants, <a href="/wiki/Ernst_%26_Young" title="Ernst &amp; Young">Ernst &amp; Young</a>.<sup id="cite_ref-goldbaum_14-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-goldbaum-14">&#91;14&#93;</a></sup> After restating their earnings, Pegasystems faced an investigation by the <a href="/wiki/United_States_Securities_and_Exchange_Commission" class="mw-redirect" title="United States Securities and Exchange Commission">SEC</a>, which was dropped in 2002.<sup id="cite_ref-sec-probe_13-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-sec-probe-13">&#91;13&#93;</a></sup>
</p>
<h3><span class="mw-headline" id="Acquisitions">Acquisitions</span><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="/w/index.php?title=Pegasystems&amp;action=edit&amp;section=3" title="Edit section: Acquisitions">edit</a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></h3>
<p>In March 2010, Pegasystems acquired the  <a href="/wiki/Enterprise_software" title="Enterprise software">enterprise software</a> company <a href="/wiki/Chordiant" title="Chordiant">Chordiant</a> for around $161.5 million.<sup id="cite_ref-chordiant-buy_15-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-chordiant-buy-15">&#91;15&#93;</a></sup>  The acquisition gave Pegasystems access to new markets such as online training, <a href="/wiki/Telecommunications" class="mw-redirect" title="Telecommunications">telecommunications</a> and healthcare, with Pegasystems integrating Chordiant and its <a href="/wiki/Customer_relationship_management" title="Customer relationship management">customer relationship management</a> (CRM) technology into its existing operations.<sup id="cite_ref-computerweekly_8-2" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-computerweekly-8">&#91;8&#93;</a></sup> Pega Cloud was introduced using <a href="/wiki/Amazon_Web_Services" title="Amazon Web Services">Amazon Web Services</a> in 2012,<sup id="cite_ref-pega-about_3-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-pega-about-3">&#91;3&#93;</a></sup> and in October 2013, Pegasystems acquired the mobile application developer <a href="/wiki/Antenna_Software" title="Antenna Software">Antenna Software</a><sup id="cite_ref-bstandard-antenna_16-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-bstandard-antenna-16">&#91;16&#93;</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-computerweekly_8-3" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-computerweekly-8">&#91;8&#93;</a></sup> for $27.7 million. Located in <a href="/wiki/New_Jersey" title="New Jersey">New Jersey</a>, Antenna also had bases in <a href="/wiki/Krak%C3%B3w" title="Kraków">Kraków</a> and <a href="/wiki/Bangalore" title="Bangalore">Bangalore</a>.<sup id="cite_ref-bstandard-antenna_16-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-bstandard-antenna-16">&#91;16&#93;</a></sup>
</p>
<h3><span class="mw-headline" id="Recent_history">Recent history</span><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="/w/index.php?title=Pegasystems&amp;action=edit&amp;section=4" title="Edit section: Recent history">edit</a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></h3>
<p>Pegasystems hired a cloud technology proponent to develop its <a href="/wiki/Cloud_technology" class="mw-redirect" title="Cloud technology">cloud technology</a> strategy in 2014. Over the following year, Pegasystems invested in network operations in <a href="/wiki/North_America" title="North America">North America</a> and <a href="/wiki/India" title="India">India</a> to support its cloud services.<sup id="cite_ref-smaller_17-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-smaller-17">&#91;17&#93;</a></sup> In May 2014, Pegasystems acquired the <a href="/wiki/Bangalore" title="Bangalore">Bangalore</a>-based MeshLabs, a text mining and analytics software startup. The <i><a href="/wiki/Times_of_India" class="mw-redirect" title="Times of India">Times of India</a></i> reported that Pegasystems would integrate MeshLabs's text analytics software to "gather unstructured social media data and decode it into actionable business insights for its clients." The financial details of the transaction were not disclosed.<sup id="cite_ref-phadnis_18-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-phadnis-18">&#91;18&#93;</a></sup> Pegasystems acquired Firefly in June 2014, a co-browsing tool funded by <a href="/wiki/First_Round_Capital" title="First Round Capital">First Round Capital</a>.<sup id="cite_ref-tc-mai_19-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-tc-mai-19">&#91;19&#93;</a></sup> The startup from <a href="/wiki/Philadelphia,_Pennsylvania" class="mw-redirect" title="Philadelphia, Pennsylvania">Philadelphia, Pennsylvania</a> was the company's first move into the <a href="/wiki/Cobrowsing" title="Cobrowsing">cobrowsing</a> market.<sup id="cite_ref-tc-mai_19-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-tc-mai-19">&#91;19&#93;</a></sup> By the summer of 2014, Pegasystems remained headquartered in <a href="/wiki/Cambridge,_Massachusetts" title="Cambridge, Massachusetts">Cambridge, Massachusetts</a> with 2,700 employees.<sup id="cite_ref-phadnis_18-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-phadnis-18">&#91;18&#93;</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-tc-mai_19-2" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-tc-mai-19">&#91;19&#93;</a></sup> By July 2014 the company was worth around US$1 billion.<sup id="cite_ref-Bglobe-trefler_7-2" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Bglobe-trefler-7">&#91;7&#93;</a></sup>
</p><p>By early 2015, Pegasystems remained a publicly traded company<sup id="cite_ref-forbes_1-7" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-forbes-1">&#91;1&#93;</a></sup> on the <a href="/wiki/Nasdaq" title="Nasdaq">Nasdaq</a>,<sup id="cite_ref-phadnis_18-2" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-phadnis-18">&#91;18&#93;</a></sup> with 3,000 employees, 30 offices, and "more than half a billion dollars in revenue."<sup id="cite_ref-forbes_1-8" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-forbes-1">&#91;1&#93;</a></sup>  As of February 2015, the company had active partnerships with IT outsourcing companies such as <a href="/w/index.php?title=Hexaware&amp;action=edit&amp;redlink=1" class="new" title="Hexaware (page does not exist)">Hexaware</a>, <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://www.incessanttechnologies.com/">NIIT Incessant Technologies</a>, <a href="/wiki/Tata_Consultancy_Services" title="Tata Consultancy Services">Tata Consultancy Services</a>, <a href="/wiki/Infosys" title="Infosys">InfosysBSE</a>, <a href="/wiki/Wipro" title="Wipro">WiproBSE</a>, <a href="/wiki/HCL_Technologies" title="HCL Technologies">HCL Technologies</a>, <a href="/wiki/Accenture" title="Accenture">Accenture</a> and <a href="/wiki/Cognizant" title="Cognizant">Cognizant</a>. By September of that year, companies who had built teams of Pegasystems specialists included Virtusa (engineering and solution delivery partner since 2001), Accenture, <a href="/wiki/Ernst_%26_Young" title="Ernst &amp; Young">Ernst &amp; Young</a> and Cognizant.<sup id="cite_ref-smaller_17-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-smaller-17">&#91;17&#93;</a></sup>  Between 2005 and 2015, Pegasystems had average sales growth of 21% per year.<sup id="cite_ref-oberweiss_20-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-oberweiss-20">&#91;20&#93;</a></sup> There was a steady rise in the company's <a href="/wiki/Share_price" title="Share price">share price</a> in 2015,<sup id="cite_ref-Yahoo2q_21-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Yahoo2q-21">&#91;21&#93;</a></sup> with higher than expected revenues from the year prior.<sup id="cite_ref-Winhoffer_22-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Winhoffer-22">&#91;22&#93;</a></sup> In January 2016, it was reported that Pegasystems planned on raising its number of employees significantly,<sup id="cite_ref-metro-cloud_23-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-metro-cloud-23">&#91;23&#93;</a></sup> and the company announced the acquisition of OpenSpan Inc. in April 2016.<sup id="cite_ref-reuters-open_24-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-reuters-open-24">&#91;24&#93;</a></sup> Based in <a href="/wiki/Atlanta,_Georgia" class="mw-redirect" title="Atlanta, Georgia">Atlanta, Georgia</a>, OpenSpan specialized in <a href="/wiki/Robotic_process_automation" title="Robotic process automation">robotic process automation</a> and workforce analytics software.<sup id="cite_ref-25" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-25">&#91;25&#93;</a></sup>
</p><p>In 2016, Pegasystems announced the launch of the Pega University Academic Program (UAP), offering training and certification on the Pega 7 platform for educators and students.<sup id="cite_ref-hans_26-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-hans-26">&#91;26&#93;</a></sup> Since 2006, the company has held an annual users' conference, PegaWorld.<sup id="cite_ref-pega-about_3-2" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-pega-about-3">&#91;3&#93;</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-B_27-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-B-27">&#91;27&#93;</a></sup> Clients&#160;<a href="/wiki/Google" title="Google">Google</a>,&#160;<a href="/wiki/Aflac" title="Aflac">Aflac</a>, and&#160;<a href="/wiki/Anthem_(company)" title="Anthem (company)">Anthem</a>&#160;gave testimonials on using Pega software at the 2018 PegaWorld conference.<sup id="cite_ref-Pegasystems_Event_in_2018_With_Testimonials_28-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Pegasystems_Event_in_2018_With_Testimonials-28">&#91;28&#93;</a></sup>
</p>
<h2><span class="mw-headline" id="Products_and_services">Products and services</span><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="/w/index.php?title=Pegasystems&amp;action=edit&amp;section=5" title="Edit section: Products and services">edit</a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></h2>
<p>Pegasystems develops and supports software<sup id="cite_ref-metro-cloud_23-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-metro-cloud-23">&#91;23&#93;</a></sup> for <a href="/wiki/Customer_engagement" title="Customer engagement">customer engagement</a><sup id="cite_ref-forbes_1-9" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-forbes-1">&#91;1&#93;</a></sup> and operations.<sup id="cite_ref-metro-cloud_23-2" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-metro-cloud-23">&#91;23&#93;</a></sup> In particular, Pegasystems specializes in software for <a href="/wiki/Business_process_management" title="Business process management">business process management</a> (BPM) and <a href="/wiki/Customer_relationship_management" title="Customer relationship management">customer relationship management</a> (CRM),<sup id="cite_ref-computerweekly_8-4" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-computerweekly-8">&#91;8&#93;</a></sup> and is seen as offering more bespoke technology than competitors such as <a href="/wiki/Oracle_Corporation" title="Oracle Corporation">Oracle Corporation</a> or <a href="/wiki/SAP_ERP" title="SAP ERP">SAP ERP</a>.<sup id="cite_ref-Digi-ceo_29-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Digi-ceo-29">&#91;29&#93;</a></sup> The company's current core software product is the Pega Platform, part of its Pega Infinity suite of applications for customer engagement and digital process automation, which are designed to connect customer interfaces with back-end process automation.<sup id="cite_ref-CMS_Wire_on_Transformation_Suite_10-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-CMS_Wire_on_Transformation_Suite-10">&#91;10&#93;</a></sup> Pegasystems states its applications are certified to work on&#160;<a href="/wiki/Google_Cloud_Platform" title="Google Cloud Platform">Google Cloud</a>&#160;and other public cloud platforms, including&#160;<a href="/wiki/Microsoft_Azure" title="Microsoft Azure">Microsoft Azure</a>,&#160;<a href="/wiki/Amazon_Web_Services" title="Amazon Web Services">Amazon Web Services</a>, and Pivotal’s&#160;<a href="/wiki/Cloud_Foundry" title="Cloud Foundry">Cloud Foundry</a>.<sup id="cite_ref-Forbes_on_Pega_Platform_Options_30-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Forbes_on_Pega_Platform_Options-30">&#91;30&#93;</a></sup> In 2018 Pega announced platform additions that used <a href="/wiki/Artificial_intelligence" title="Artificial intelligence">artificial intelligence</a> for marketing campaigns, customer interfaces, and robotic automation, as well as a&#160;<a href="/wiki/Blockchain" title="Blockchain">Blockchain</a>&#160;kit for <a href="/wiki/Ethereum" title="Ethereum">Ethereum</a>.<sup id="cite_ref-Infinity_Product_with_Pegasystems_and_CRM_31-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Infinity_Product_with_Pegasystems_and_CRM-31">&#91;31&#93;</a></sup>
</p><p>As of late 2013, Pegasystem’s core software, PegaRULES Process Commander (PRPC), was related to BPM.<sup id="cite_ref-computerweekly_8-5" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-computerweekly-8">&#91;8&#93;</a></sup> Pegasystems Inc. in March 2016 announced Pega Client Lifecycle Management (CLM), an application "that streamlines and automates corporate client onboarding" for banks by "[orchestrating] complex CLM processes on a global scale in a single application, reducing onboarding time by 70 percent and reducing costs by 60 percent."<sup id="cite_ref-forbes-earn_32-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-forbes-earn-32">&#91;32&#93;</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-kurmanath_33-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-kurmanath-33">&#91;33&#93;</a></sup> The company has added artificial intelligence into its customer service software to allow interactions to occur on multiple communication channels at once.<sup id="cite_ref-34" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-34">&#91;34&#93;</a></sup> The company’s <a href="/wiki/Low-code_development_platforms" class="mw-redirect" title="Low-code development platforms">low-code development platform</a> was highlighted in a 2018 <i><a href="/wiki/Wall_Street_Journal" class="mw-redirect" title="Wall Street Journal">Wall Street Journal</a></i> article, with Pegasystems’ chief technology officer explaining that the software allowed developers to "drag and drop [ready-made software components] to configure applications,” minimizing development time.<sup id="cite_ref-35" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-35">&#91;35&#93;</a></sup>
</p><p>In April 2020, Pegasystems Inc. announced the launch of a Crisis Small Business Lending reference application which helps financial institutions manage emergency loan applications from small businesses seeking COVID-19 financial relief.<sup id="cite_ref-36" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-36">&#91;36&#93;</a></sup>
</p>
<h2><span class="mw-headline" id="Clients_and_notable_projects">Clients and notable projects</span><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="/w/index.php?title=Pegasystems&amp;action=edit&amp;section=6" title="Edit section: Clients and notable projects">edit</a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></h2>
<p>Pegasystems specializes in the following industries: <a href="/wiki/Financial_services" title="Financial services">financial services</a>,<sup id="cite_ref-metro-cloud_23-3" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-metro-cloud-23">&#91;23&#93;</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-AMB-mellon_37-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-AMB-mellon-37">&#91;37&#93;</a></sup> <a href="/wiki/Insurance_industry" class="mw-redirect" title="Insurance industry">insurance</a>, <a href="/wiki/Life_sciences" class="mw-redirect" title="Life sciences">life sciences</a>, <a href="/wiki/Healthcare_industry" title="Healthcare industry">healthcare</a>,<sup id="cite_ref-metro-cloud_23-4" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-metro-cloud-23">&#91;23&#93;</a></sup> government, manufacturing,<sup id="cite_ref-metro-cloud_23-5" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-metro-cloud-23">&#91;23&#93;</a></sup> <a href="/wiki/High_technology" class="mw-redirect" title="High technology">high tech</a>,<sup id="cite_ref-Bglobe-trefler_7-3" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Bglobe-trefler-7">&#91;7&#93;</a></sup> communications and media, <a href="/wiki/Energy_industry" title="Energy industry">energy</a>, and <a href="/wiki/Utilities" class="mw-redirect" title="Utilities">utilities</a>. While core areas have traditionally included banking and financial sectors, more recent areas include manufacturing, life sciences and healthcare.<sup id="cite_ref-metro-cloud_23-6" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-metro-cloud-23">&#91;23&#93;</a></sup> As of 2013, other clients included "largely Fortune 500 companies" such as <a href="/wiki/ING" class="mw-redirect" title="ING">ING</a>, <a href="/wiki/Lloyds_Banking_Group" title="Lloyds Banking Group">Lloyds Banking Group</a>, <a href="/wiki/Heathrow_Airport_Holdings" title="Heathrow Airport Holdings">BAA</a>,<sup id="cite_ref-computerweekly_8-6" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-computerweekly-8">&#91;8&#93;</a></sup>  and the state of <a href="/wiki/Maine" title="Maine">Maine</a>, which commissioned Pegasystems to create a BPM system to cut administrative costs. By July 2014, <a href="/wiki/PayPal" title="PayPal">PayPal</a>, <a href="/wiki/Cisco_Systems" title="Cisco Systems">Cisco Systems</a>, and <a href="/wiki/Philips" title="Philips">Philips</a> were using Pegasystems’ CRM software,<sup id="cite_ref-Bglobe-trefler_7-4" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Bglobe-trefler-7">&#91;7&#93;</a></sup>  and <a href="/wiki/BNY_Mellon" class="mw-redirect" title="BNY Mellon">BNY Mellon</a> announced they would be integrating Pega into its operations as part of their efficiency strategy.<sup id="cite_ref-AMB-mellon_37-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-AMB-mellon-37">&#91;37&#93;</a></sup>
</p>
<h2><span class="mw-headline" id="Pega_Ventures_Program">Pega Ventures Program</span><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="/w/index.php?title=Pegasystems&amp;action=edit&amp;section=7" title="Edit section: Pega Ventures Program">edit</a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></h2>
<p>Pegasystems operates a Pega Ventures Program that invests in privately owned companies.<sup class="noprint Inline-Template Template-Fact" style="white-space:nowrap;">&#91;<i><a href="/wiki/Wikipedia:Citation_needed" title="Wikipedia:Citation needed"><span title="This claim needs references to reliable sources. (May 2020)">citation needed</span></a></i>&#93;</sup>
</p>
